		IAM conditions & impersonantion (Phase 2)

Topic - IAM Advanced: service Account Impersonantion Delegagtgion,
Conditional IAM Bindings (Time-bases), Least Privilege Resource Scoping

##Objective 

- Learn how to impersonate a service account using another service account (delegation Chain) 

- Understand short-lived token generation via IAM Credentials API 

- Practice least-privilege access using bucket-leve IAM bindings

- Observe allow vs deny behavior with impersonated tokens 

- Identify and remove uncondition IAM bindings to enforce conditional logic 



##Key Concepts 

- Impersonation Chain 
User -> securitay-sa-> workload-sa->resource 

- TokenCreator Role: required for generating access tokens on behalf of another SA

- IAM conditions: add contextual logic (time-based) to access control 

- conditional vs unconditional bindings: unconditional superseeds 

- Time-based lockout: using request.time to enforce access windows 

- 403 premissionDenied confirms IAM is enforced correctly 

- storage IAM limitations: bucket IAM does not support IP-Based conditions 

- Short-lived tokens, no key files required (safer and auditable) 


## Practical work 

- Creates 2 service accounts
 -- workload-sa (target identity)
 -- security-sa (delegator identity)

- Granted Tokencreator role 
 -- User->security-sa
 --security-sa -> workload-sa

- enabled IAM credentials API 

- Generated a delegated impersonation token for workload-sa using security-sa

- successfuly accessed 
 -- allowed bucket -> 200 OK 
 -- Forbidden Bucket -> 403 Premission denied 

- Create a TIme-based IAM condition on the allowed bucket using request.time
- removed the unconditional objectViewer binding 
- Verified the bucket now respects ONLY the time-conditiond rule 
- confirmed conditional access works inside window and denies outside 

Confusions / Struggles
•	IP based conditions failed → Storage IAM does not support request.client_ip
•	Unclear initial distinction between unconditional and conditional IAM bindings
•	Removing the unconditional binding required specifying --condition=None
•	Delegate impersonation via gcloud does not use 
	--impersonate-service-account-delegates; must use IAM Credentials API instead
•	Understanding how delegated impersonation differs from direct impersonation
•	General feeling of executing commands without deep understanding 
	(will improve with new training structure)



Mental Model
“IAM identity is who you are, IAM Condition is when and in what context 
you can act.
Impersonation is borrowing another identity under strict, auditable rules.
Conditional IAM turns identity into zero trust access by adding time, context, 
and logic.”
Breakdown:
•	workload-sa → Least-privilege identity
•	security-sa → Controlled impersonator
•	User → Initiator of impersonation chain
•	IAM Credentials API → Issues short lived tokens
•	request.time → Gatekeeper for time windows
•	Conditional binding → Active only when expression is true
•	403 PermissionDenied → IAM behaving correctly
•	IAM is not networking → Storage IAM cannot filter by client IP; 
	use VPC SC or Cloud Armor for perimeter logic
